{"key":"processedPost-10881382","value":{"id":10881382,"first":10881293,"last":10881982,"when":1250606670,"utime":"08/18/09 05:44 PM","cleanedPost":"Split the stem down the middle by tearing it like a piece of string cheese.&nbsp; Cut a tiny sample no bigger than a grain of rice from the middle of the stem and place on agar.&nbsp; Don't dip in peroxide, bleach or anything. You only need that when cloning outdoor wild mushrooms.<br />As soon as it starts growing, transfer a few tiny pieces from the leading edge of the growth to new petri dishes.&nbsp; This way, you'll grab nice mycelium ahead of any mold or bacteria that may develop later. You might find the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Mushroom-Cloning\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">cloning page</a> and video clip from my website helpful.<br />RR"}}